text.73:
RFC: Adding Python Backend to Nim Compiler

Introduction:
Nim, being a language with extensive metaprogramming capabilities and a focus on performance, has become a popular choice for software development. The Nim compiler, being the backbone of the language, has been improving over time. However, Nim does not currently have a backend for the popular Python programming language. This RFC proposes the addition of a Python backend to the Nim compiler.

Goals:
The primary goal of the Python backend is to allow Nim programmers to target the Python ecosystem with ease. With this backend, it will be possible to write Nim code that compiles into Python code that can be executed by standard Python runtimes.

Implementation:
The Python backend will be developed as a backend for the Nim compiler. It will generate Python code from Nim code. The backend will be implemented in the Nim programming language itself.

The backend will be developed as a separate module that will be included with the Nim compiler distribution. This will ensure that users who do not need the Python backend do not have to install it.

The Nim compiler will be modified to recognize the `--backend:python` option. This option will instruct the Nim compiler to use the Python backend instead of the default backend. Additionally, the Python backend will provide its own set of standard library modules that will match the Python standard library as closely as possible.

Compatibility:
The Python backend will support Python versions 3.6 and above. It will not support Python 2.x versions. Compatibility with popular Python frameworks, such as Django and Flask, will be a priority.

Conclusion:
The addition of a Python backend to the Nim compiler will be a valuable addition to the Nim ecosystem. It will allow Nim programmers to target the Python ecosystem with ease, while taking advantage of Nim's performance and metaprogramming capabilities.
